  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is raw honey healthier than pasteurized honey?",
  "response": "Raw honey and pasteurized honey have some differences in terms of health benefits, but the extent of these differences can vary.\n\n**Raw Honey:**\n- **Nutritional Content:** Raw honey is honey that has not been heated or processed. It contains more natural nutrients such as pollen, enzymes, antioxidants, and other beneficial compounds.\n- **Enzymes and Antioxidants:** Since raw honey is not heated, it retains more enzymes and antioxidants which may have health benefits, such as aiding digestion and reducing inflammation.\n- **Potential Risks:** Raw honey may contain spores of Clostridium botulinum, which can be harmful to infants under one year old, leading to infant botulism. It is advised not to give raw honey to infants.\n\n**Pasteurized Honey:**\n- **Processing:** Pasteurized honey is heated to high temperatures to kill off yeast cells and extend shelf life. This process can also make honey clearer and more aesthetically pleasing.\n- **Nutrient Loss:** The heating process can destroy some of the beneficial enzymes, pollen, and antioxidants found in raw honey.\n- **Safety:** Pasteurization kills off any potential bacteria or spores, making it safer for all age groups, including infants.\n\n**In Summary:**\n- Raw honey generally retains more beneficial nutrients and may offer more health benefits due to its higher content of enzymes and antioxidants.\n- Pasteurized honey is safer for consumption by all age groups and has a longer shelf life, but it may have fewer health benefits due to nutrient loss during processing.\n\nIf you're looking for the potential health benefits of honey, raw honey might be the better choice. However, if safety and a longer shelf life are more important to you, pasteurized honey is a good option.",
